05652nam a22010335i 9780228009719DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280097197 a10.1515/97802280097192doi  a(DE-B1597)655064  a(OCoLC)1252062414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKEO724b.K64 2021 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a344.71304/82231 aKoester, C. Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Public Good :bEugenics and Law in Ontario /cC. Elizabeth Koester. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b16 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Associated Medical Services Studies in the History of Medicine, Health, and Society ;v5700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note about Vocabulary -- tIntroduction -- tPlaces and People -- tLegislating Eugenics: Dr Forbes Godfrey and His Private Member's Bills -- tInvestigating Eugenics: Three Ontario Royal Commissions -- tEugenics on Trial: A.R. Kaufman, the Parents' Information Bureau, and the Eastview Birth-Control Trial -- tConclusion -- tGodfrey's Sterilization and Marriage Bills -- tGovernment's Successful Marriage Act Amendment -- tSection 207 of the Criminal Code -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early twentieth century, the eugenics movement won many supporters with its promise that social ills such as venereal disease, alcoholism, and so-called feeble-mindedness, along with many other conditions, could be eliminated by selective human breeding and other measures. The provinces of Alberta and British Columbia passed legislation requiring that certain “unfit” individuals undergo reproductive sterilization. Ontario, being home to many leading proponents of eugenics, came close to doing the same.In the Public Good examines three legal processes that were used to advance eugenic ideas in Ontario between 1910 and 1938: legislative bills, provincial royal commissions, and the criminal trial of a young woman accused of distributing birth control information. Taken together, they reveal who in the province supported these ideas, how they were understood in relation to the public good, and how they were debated. Elizabeth Koester shows the ways in which the law was used both to promote and to deflect eugenics, and how the concept of the public good was used by supporters to add power to their cause.With eugenic thinking finding new footholds in the possibilities offered by reproductive technologies, proposals to link welfare entitlement to “voluntary” sterilization, and concerns about immigration, In the Public Good adds depth to our understanding. Its exploration of the historical relationship between eugenics and law in Ontario prepares us to face the implications of “newgenics” today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEugenicsxLaw and legislationzOntarioxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  a1900s.  a1910s.  a1920s.  a1930s.  aClifford Magone.  aCriminal Code.  aDorothea Palmer.  aESC.  aEastview Trial.  aEugenics Society Canada.  aF E Hodgins.  aForbes Godfrey.  aFrancis Galton.  aFrank Hodgins.  aHelen MacMurchy.  aHerbert Bruce.  aKaufman.  aOntario.  aP D Ross.  aParents Information Bureau.  aRoman Catholic church.  aToronto.  aW L Hutton.  abirth control.  afeeble minded.  afit.  afitness.  agreat depression.  aimmigration.  aindividual liberty.  amarriage laws.  anegative.  aobscenity provisions.  apositive.  aprivate members bills.  aradio broadcasts. 